 Adapted from the great French philosopher Rene Descartes, the systematic observation of nature is a prerequisite to the scientific method of enquiry. This requirement, having originated in the time of the ancient Greeks, has been maintained throughout the ages and is, in modern times, considered to have been formalized by Karl Popper in his book, Conjectures and refutations. This requirement involves the formulation of the following three axioms, which are mutually equivalent in their effect: 1.
